Grouping the data

The contents of each file is combined into one dataframe called as x. The data is grouped according to the parameter of ethnicity: white vs.Asian. EdgeR provides a simplified method of doing this with a single command: readDGE.

x <- readDGE(files, columns=c(1,2))
## Meta tags detected: __no_feature, __ambiguous, __too_low_aQual, __not_aligned, __alignment_not_unique
class(x)
## [1] "DGEList"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "edgeR"

The newly created dataframe x can be checked for its dimensions to see if the readDGE command worked.

dim(x)
## [1] 60487    40

The dim function shows that there are 60487 rows (which represents genes) and 40 columns. The 40 columns represents the 40 files (20 Asian females and 20 white females).

The code block below will help to label all the columns in dataframe x according to the respective files.

samplenames<-colnames(x)
sampleNames
## standardGeneric for "sampleNames" defined from package "Biobase"
## 
## function (object) 
## standardGeneric("sampleNames")
## <bytecode: 0x7fdcdd7ee848>
## <environment: 0x7fdcdd7df850>
## Methods may be defined for arguments: object
## Use  showMethods("sampleNames")  for currently available ones.
colnames(x) <- samplenames

Organizing the data

x$samples$group <- group

Because the Homo.sapiens package does not contain the ENSEMBL Gene ID in the format provided by the loaded data, the data must be converted using a substitution function. The digits following the decimal are replaced to match with the key.

library(gsubfn)
## Loading required package: proto
## Warning in doTryCatch(return(expr), name, parentenv, handler): unable to load shared object '/Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Resources/modules//R_X11.so':
##   dlopen(/Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Resources/modules//R_X11.so, 6): Library not loaded: /opt/X11/lib/libSM.6.dylib
##   Referenced from: /Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Resources/modules//R_X11.so
##   Reason: image not found
## Could not load tcltk.  Will use slower R code instead.
geneid <- rownames(x)
geneid <-gsub("\\.[0-9]*$","", geneid)
head(geneid)
## [1] "ENSG00000000005" "ENSG00000000419" "ENSG00000000457" "ENSG00000000460"
## [5] "ENSG00000000938" "ENSG00000000971"

The genes dataframe is used to store the gene-level information corresponding to the rows of genes in our patient data files. The information required for this data frame is retrieved from the Homo.sapiens library. The GeneIDs are associated with the symbol and the chromosome number of each gene.

genes <- select(Homo.sapiens, keys=geneid, columns=c("SYMBOL", "TXCHROM"), 
                keytype="ENSEMBL")
## 'select()' returned 1:many mapping between keys and columns
head(genes)
##           ENSEMBL   SYMBOL TXCHROM
## 1 ENSG00000000005     TNMD    chrX
## 2 ENSG00000000419     DPM1   chr20
## 3 ENSG00000000457    SCYL3    chr1
## 4 ENSG00000000460 C1orf112    chr1
## 5 ENSG00000000938      FGR    chr1
## 6 ENSG00000000971      CFH    chr1

Any duplicated genes are removed from the dataset.

genes <- genes[!duplicated(genes$ENSEMBL),]
x$genes <- genes

Data Pre-processing

Transformations from the raw scale

The data is transformed from its raw form to more useable. The calculations of cpm: counts per million and lcpm: log of counts per million are carried out to do so.

cpm <- cpm(x)
lcpm <- cpm(x, log=TRUE)

For further calculations the data is processed using the calculations below. L is the average library size in millions. M is the median of the library size in millions.

L <- mean(x$samples$lib.size) * 1e-6
M <- median(x$samples$lib.size) * 1e-6
c(L, M)
## [1] 92.39128 87.39270

Removing genes that are lowly expressed

Some genes are lowly expressed and do not contribute to the statistical analysis in a meaningful manner. These are genes that are lowly expressed in both of the data groups. To understand the ratio of these genes, the following line is run:

table(rowSums(x$counts==0)==9)
## 
## FALSE  TRUE 
## 59997   490

EdgeR helps to filter out these lowly expressed genes rather easily:

keep.exprs <- filterByExpr(x, group=group)
x <- x[keep.exprs,, keep.lib.sizes=FALSE]
dim(x)
## [1] 20886    40

The number of genes used for interpretation are reduced from the 60,487 to 20886. The filtered versus unfiltered data is presented in a graphical manner using the following lines of code. The package RColorBrewer is used to help create the graphs.

lcpm.cutoff <- log2(10/M + 2/L)
library(RColorBrewer)
nsamples <- ncol(x)
col <- brewer.pal(nsamples, "Paired")
## Warning in brewer.pal(nsamples, "Paired"): n too large, allowed maximum for palette Paired is 12
## Returning the palette you asked for with that many colors
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(density(lcpm[,1]), col=col[1], lwd=2, ylim=c(0,0.26), las=2, main="", xlab="")
title(main="A. Raw data", xlab="Log-cpm")
abline(v=lcpm.cutoff, lty=3)
for (i in 2:nsamples){
den <- density(lcpm[,i])
lines(den$x, den$y, col=col[i], lwd=2)
}
legend("topright", samplenames, text.col=col, bty="n")
lcpm <- cpm(x, log=TRUE)
plot(density(lcpm[,1]), col=col[1], lwd=2, ylim=c(0,0.26), las=2, main="", xlab="")
title(main="B. Filtered data", xlab="Log-cpm")
abline(v=lcpm.cutoff, lty=3)
for (i in 2:nsamples){
den <- density(lcpm[,i])
lines(den$x, den$y, col=col[i], lwd=2)
}
legend("topright", samplenames, text.col=col, bty="n")

Normalizing gene expression distributions

For statistical analysis, the normalization of data is greatly beneficial. Normalization should be performed to ensure that the expression distributions of each sample are similar across the entire experiment. edgeR offers a function to do this. The resulting values are stored in a data set called norm.factors.

x <- calcNormFactors(x, method = "TMM")
x$samples$norm.factors
##  [1] 1.0032234 1.0249509 1.0562917 1.1129549 1.1226787 1.1167543 0.9596554
##  [8] 1.1044366 1.1364243 0.9686791 1.1551560 1.0330608 1.0444397 1.1166399
## [15] 0.6367315 0.8413959 0.8967112 0.9740954 0.8563486 0.9988445 1.0334991
## [22] 1.1014337 1.0140630 1.2868320 0.9065866 0.9438617 0.5562950 1.0281427
## [29] 0.7430484 0.9048054 1.2171299 1.1786699 1.2897168 1.1186813 1.2956297
## [36] 0.9018703 0.7829183 0.9488794 1.0550795 1.0956067

To understand this effect the data is manipulated in such a way that the counts of the first sample are reduced to 5% and the second is increased by 500%.

x2 <- x
x2$samples$norm.factors <- 1
x2$counts[,1] <- ceiling(x2$counts[,1]*0.05)
x2$counts[,2] <- x2$counts[,2]*5

The plots below shows data that is normalized versus non-normalized.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
lcpm <- cpm(x2, log=TRUE)

Unsupervised clustering of samples

The MDS plot is an informative representation of the similarities and dissimilarities in a sample. The extent of the differences can give an idea of the expected results of the differential expression analysis. The plotMDS function of limma allows us to create the graph. The distances on the plot correspond to the action of different categories on this data.

lcpm <- cpm(x, log=TRUE)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
group
##  [1] "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian"
## [10] "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian" "Asian"
## [19] "Asian" "Asian" "white" "white" "white" "white" "white" "white" "white"
## [28] "white" "white" "white" "white" "white" "white" "white" "white" "white"
## [37] "white" "white" "white" "white"
levels(group) <-  brewer.pal(nlevels(group), "Set1")
## Warning in brewer.pal(nlevels(group), "Set1"): minimal value for n is 3, returning requested palette with 3 different levels
col.group <- as.character(group)
col.group <- c("purple","orange")[group]
plotMDS(lcpm, labels=group, col=col.group)
title(main="A. Sample groups")

Glimma can be used to create an interactive version of the plot above.

glMDSPlot(lcpm,groups = group)

In these two plots, the relationship between the mean and variances of the data are plot. The first graph represents the relationship before the data is normalized using voom and second, after. The effect of normalization can be visualized through the lines of best fit.

vfit <- lmFit(v, design)
vfit <- contrasts.fit(vfit, contrasts=contr.matrix)
efit <- eBayes(vfit)
plotSA(efit, main="Final model: Mean-variance trend")

Examining the number of differentially expressed genes

T-statistics can be used to help see how many genes are significantly up-regulated or down-regulated. In the table below, we see that 6 genes are down-regulated and 7 genes are up-regulated.

summary(decideTests(efit))
##        AsianVswhite
## Down              6
## NotSig        20873
## Up                7

Additional filtering of significantly DF genes may be done by using the treat method, which requires genes to have a log-FC greater than 1.

tfit <- treat(vfit, lfc=0.1)
dt <- decideTests(tfit)
summary(dt)
##        AsianVswhite
## Down              6
## NotSig        20873
## Up                7

All genes, up-regulated or down-regulated included, are in the list below.

de.common <- which(dt[,1]!=0)
length(de.common)
## [1] 13

We can see the names of the genes from the de.common list using the following code:

head(tfit$genes$SYMBOL[de.common], n=20)
##  [1] "ATP10B"    NA          "KCNG3"     "NPIPB15"   "SCAMP5"    "AGAP9"    
##  [7] NA          NA          NA          NA          "LLPH-DT"   NA         
## [13] "ADAMTS7P1"

The vennDiagram function can be used to visualize the DE genes that the Asian female patients and white female patients share.

vennDiagram(dt[,1], circle.col=c("turquoise", "salmon"))

write.fit(tfit, dt, file="results.txt")

Examining individual DE genes from top to bottom

The genes that are most differentially expressed can be listed using the toptreat function.

Asian.vs.white <- topTreat(tfit, coef=1, n=Inf)

Using graphical representations of differential expression results

To summarise the genes, the log fold change is plot against the log counts per million using the plotMD function.

plotMD(tfit, column=1, status=dt[,1], main=colnames(tfit)[1], 
       xlim=c(-8,13))

A more interactive version of this plot can be created using Glimma.

glMDPlot(tfit, coef=1, status=dt, main=colnames(tfit)[1],
         side.main="ENSEMBL", counts=lcpm, groups=group, launch=TRUE)

A heatmap is created of the highest expressed genes. Heatmap.plus is a library that allows for the creation of heatmaps for larger datasets. First, load up the required packages.

library(gplots)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:IRanges':
## 
##     space
## The following object is masked from 'package:S4Vectors':
## 
##     space
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
library(heatmap.plus)

Next, execute the following code:

Asian.vs.white.topgenes <- Asian.vs.white$ENSEMBL[1:50]
i <- which(v$genes$ENSEMBL %in% Asian.vs.white.topgenes)
mycol <- colorpanel(1000,"blue","white","red")
par(cex.main=0.8,mar=c(1,1,1,1))
heatmap.plus(lcpm[i,],  scale="row", labRow=v$genes$SYMBOL[i], labCol=group, col=mycol, cexRow=1,cexCol=0.2, margins = c(8,6), main="HeatMap")

In the heatmap produced, the red regions stand for up-regulated genes, blue regions represent down-regulated genes, and white presents intermediate levels of genes expression.
